# Cursor Rules — Shyre

> These rules are identical to `CLAUDE.md`. If you update one, update the other.
>
> Persona sync is stricter: every persona has three files (`docs/personas/<name>.md`, `.claude/agents/<name>.md`, `.cursor/rules/persona-<name>.mdc`) that must move together.

## Project

Shyre is a platform for running a consulting business. Time tracking + invoicing ship as the `stint` module inside it. Next.js 16 (App Router) + Supabase + Tailwind CSS 4. Deployed on Vercel. Shared UI / theme / tokens come from `@theshyre/*`.

## Time-entry authorship — MANDATORY

Every time entry displayed anywhere must show the author via `<Avatar>` from `@theshyre/ui` + `user_profiles.display_name`. Applies to time-entries list, reports, dashboard, customer + project detail, invoice line items, trash — anywhere a `time_entries` row surfaces. Consistent behavior across solo + team scenarios, not conditional on author count. See `CLAUDE.md` → "Time-entry authorship — MANDATORY".

## TypeScript — strict, no exceptions

- `strict: true` + `noUncheckedIndexedAccess`. Never loosen.
- No `any` — use `unknown` and narrow, or define a proper type.
- No `@ts-ignore`, `@ts-expect-error`, or `eslint-disable`.
- No non-null assertions (`!`) unless guarded in the same scope.
- Explicit return types on exported functions and server actions.
- Handle all error cases — no swallowed catches.
- Use `import type` for type-only imports.

## File organization

- Co-locate tests: `actions.test.ts` next to `actions.ts`
- Co-locate page components with routes: `clients/new-client-form.tsx`
- Shared components in `src/components/`, hooks in `src/hooks/`, types in `src/types/`

## Naming

- SQL columns: `snake_case`
- TypeScript: `camelCase` for variables/interfaces
- Components: `PascalCase`, filenames: `kebab-case`
- Server actions: `verbNounAction`

## Supabase

- Server Components: `createClient()` from `@/lib/supabase/server`
- Client Components: `createClient()` from `@/lib/supabase/client`
- Server Actions: always verify `auth.getUser()` first
- RLS handles authorization — never bypass it

## Shared packages — @theshyre/* (MANDATORY)

Shyre consumes `@theshyre/ui`, `@theshyre/theme`, `@theshyre/design-tokens` from GitHub Packages. Source is `/Users/marcus/projects/theshyre-core`. Liv consumes the same packages. All three repos stay in step.

- **Stay on latest.** Shyre's `@theshyre/*` carets in `package.json` must be ≥ the latest published version. When `theshyre-core` publishes, bump + install + `typecheck`/`lint`/`test`/`build` same day. No carrying drift into the next feature commit.
- **TS compiler + `@types/node` major** track `theshyre-core` and Liv. A TS major is a cross-repo change, never Shyre-local.
- **Promotion criteria — all four required.** Code belongs in `@theshyre/*` only when:
  1. App-agnostic (no time entries, invoices, customers, projects, teams domain).
  2. No Supabase / no DB knowledge.
  3. React 19 + Next 16 compatible.
  4. Concrete consumer beyond Shyre — Liv uses it or is planned to. "Could be generic" isn't enough.
- **Author generic primitives in-core first.** Before writing a new generic utility/hook/component in Shyre, stop and author it in `theshyre-core/packages/ui`. Import from `@theshyre/ui`. Avoid the "inline today, promote later" churn.
- **Promotion workflow.** PR in `theshyre-core` (add + tests + changeset). `pnpm version-packages` → commit → push → `pnpm release`. Then a Shyre PR bumps the caret, deletes local copies (or converts to re-exports), rewires imports. Never merge the Shyre side before `npm view @theshyre/<pkg> version` confirms publish.
- **Re-export wrappers** (`src/components/Foo.tsx` → `export { Foo } from "@theshyre/ui";`) are valid only when the wrapper adds i18n labels (`SaveStatus`, `InlineDeleteButton`) or call sites are entrenched on the `@/components/Foo` path. Not for their own sake.
- **App-specific stays in Shyre.** `EntryAuthor`, `InvoicePDF`, `Timer`, `Sidebar`, `TeamFilter`, server actions, `safe-action.ts`, RLS helpers, Supabase clients, Next.js routes, Shyre Zod schemas, Shyre i18n bundles. These are never promotion candidates — if the concept moves, create a new package, don't stuff it into `@theshyre/ui`.

## Migrations & deploy ordering (MANDATORY)

Vercel (app code) and `.github/workflows/db-migrate.yml` (SQL migrations) run in **parallel** on every push to `main`. There is no sequencing.

- **Additive** (`ADD COLUMN`, `CREATE TABLE/INDEX/POLICY`, nullable FK, new enum value): safe to ship code + migration in one PR. Use `IF NOT EXISTS` for idempotency. A brief window where one is live without the other is harmless.
- **Destructive** (`DROP COLUMN/TABLE`, `ALTER ... NOT NULL` without default, narrowing a type): **two PRs, never one.**
  1. PR 1: remove every code reference to the thing. Merge, wait for Vercel.
  2. PR 2: the migration alone. Merge.
- **Renames**: expand-contract. Add new column → backfill + dual-write → flip reads → drop old column, across multiple PRs. See `rename_organizations_to_teams` as the reference pattern.
- **Timestamps must be monotonic**: check the latest file under `supabase/migrations/` and use a strictly-later timestamp so `supabase db push` doesn't require `--include-all`.
- **Allow-lists ↔ CHECK constraints must match.** App-level `ALLOWED_*` sets live in `allow-lists.ts` siblings of their action files; `src/__tests__/db-parity.test.ts` compares each to the effective CHECK constraint in migrations. Adding a value requires widening the constraint in the same PR.
- `SUPABASE_DB_URL` repo secret is required for prod migrations. If the GH Action fails for a missing secret, that's a fire, not a warning.
- Don't disable the `db-verify.yml` PR check to merge — red means the migration is broken.

## Gates (MANDATORY — CI enforces these)

`.github/workflows/ci.yml` runs on every push and PR. All three must pass:

- **`npm run lint`** exits zero with `--max-warnings=0`. Warnings = errors.
  - No `eslint-disable` to make it pass. Fix the code. For true exceptions, add a file-scoped override in `eslint.config.mjs` with a written rationale.
- **`npm run typecheck`** (`tsc --noEmit`) exits zero. No `any`, no `@ts-ignore`.
- **`npm run test`** passes. Every new file needs a test. Vitest for unit, Playwright for E2E.

Run all three locally before declaring work complete. "Run lint later" is not a plan.

## Testing (>90% coverage)

- Vitest for unit + integration, Playwright for E2E
- Every new file needs a test file — no exceptions
- Test behavior, not implementation. Cover error paths and edge cases.
- **Pre-commit**: run `npm run ci:local` (lint + typecheck + test:coverage) before every commit that adds production code. The CI coverage gate is set just below the current measured number; shipping new code without tests trips it. Reproducing locally is faster than a 3-minute CI round-trip.

## Security

- MFA support (TOTP) from day one
- No secrets in code — env vars only
- No string interpolation in queries — use parameterized methods
- Validate all user input in server actions
- GitHub tokens are secrets — never log or return in list queries

## Form & button rules (MANDATORY)

Every form:
- Submits on Enter (native `<form>` + submit button)
- Autofocuses the primary field on open
- Uses SubmitButton from @/components/SubmitButton for spinner + disabled state
- Disables Cancel during pending
- Shows serverError inline + FieldError below fields

Every button:
- Uses shared button classes from @/lib/form-styles
- Shows loading state for async actions
- Disabled buttons look disabled (not ambiguous)
- Never silently succeeds or fails

Destructive flows (by what is actually being destroyed):
- **Unsaved local state** (row user added but never committed) → inline `<InlineDeleteButton />`. Nothing to undo.
- **Row-level delete of persisted data** → typed-confirm via `<InlineDeleteRowConfirm />`; user types `delete` (case-insensitive) to arm. Inline expansion, not modal. Soft-delete + 10s Undo toast + `/trash` recovery are orthogonal — they apply on top.
- **Multi-entity or record-level** (delete customer/project/team, void invoice) → typed-name confirmation using the entity's own name.
- **Irreversible hard delete from trash** → inline `<InlineDeleteButton />` with "forever" label (second-click safety after the user already decided to trash it).
- HIDE the original trigger when the confirmation form is shown. Cancel button + Escape key always work.

## Multi-select tables (MANDATORY)

Tables with row selection + bulk actions use one of two patterns. Pick by **column count**.

**Pattern A — overlay strip (≤ 8 semantic columns).** Bulk strip absolute-positions OVER the thead; column headers stay mounted in DOM but visually replaced. Reference: `src/app/(dashboard)/time-entries/entry-table.tsx`.

**Pattern B — sibling strip above (> 8 semantic columns).** Bulk strip renders as a SIBLING above the `<table>`, inside the same bordered container. Headers stay fully visible. Reference: `src/app/(dashboard)/business/[businessId]/expenses/expenses-table.tsx`.

Common rules:
- **Zero CLS on selection toggle** — vertical or horizontal. Column widths owned by a `<colgroup>` with `table-fixed`; strip never mutates `colSpan`, never reserves empty space, never pushes rows.
- **Master checkbox** shows indeterminate when partial. **Escape clears selection** when no more-specific handler is active.
- **Inline ack message in the strip on success**, alongside the count + clear button (don't replace them). Toast at viewport bottom is the persistent record.
- **Bulk action handlers must check `result.success`** from `runSafeAction`-wrapped server actions. On failure: error toast + re-throw.
- **Destructive bulk actions** use `<InlineDeleteRowConfirm />` + Undo toast.

Pattern-A specifics: ResizeObserver-measured height; `aria-hidden` the `<thead>`; thead master checkbox `tabIndex={-1}`.

Pattern-B specifics: regular `<div role="toolbar">` before the `<table>` in the same bordered container; no aria-hidden / ResizeObserver / tabIndex plumbing.

**Do not extract to `@theshyre/ui` yet** — Shyre owns the pattern in-place until Liv adopts it.

Surfaces:
- Pattern A: `/time-entries` (day + week).
- Pattern B: `/business/[id]/expenses`, `/customers`, `/projects`, `/invoices`, `/trash`, any future wide table.

## Typography (MANDATORY)

- Semantic scale defined in `globals.css`: `text-label` / `text-caption` / `text-body` / `text-body-lg` / `text-title` / `text-page-title` / `text-hero`. All rem-based so the text-size preference scales the whole UI.
- **Never use `text-[Npx]` or raw `text-xs/sm/base/lg/xl`** in new code — they bypass the scale.
- Pair semantic size with `font-normal/medium/semibold/bold` as needed. Weights are orthogonal.
- Monetary/time values: `font-mono tabular-nums` + one of the scale classes.
- Table headers: `text-label font-semibold uppercase text-content-muted`. Page titles: `text-page-title font-bold text-content`.

## Text size preference

- Compact / Regular / Large applied via `data-text-size` on `<html>` + root font-size. Persisted in `user_settings.text_size`, mirrored to localStorage for anti-flash. Source of truth in `@/components/text-size-provider`.
- Themes: `system`, `light`, `dark`, `high-contrast`, `warm`. Warm palette matches Liv.

## Layout dimensions in px, type in rem (MANDATORY)

The `<html>` font-size override above scales every `rem` with the text-size preference. Good for type, bad for layout — without this rule sidebars widen and gutters shift when a viewer toggles to Large. Source of truth: `theshyre-core/CLAUDE.md`; enforced per-app.

- **Layout → px (Tailwind arbitrary values).** Sidebar widths, page max-widths, structural gutters between independent regions, popover/dropdown widths, scroll-container `max-h-*`, fixed table column widths. Use `w-[256px]`, `max-w-[1280px]`, `px-[32px]`, `gap-[24px]`, `max-h-[240px]`.
- **Type and text-adjacent padding → rem.** All `text-*` scale, line-heights, button/cell/nav row internal padding, paragraph reading-measure (`max-w-3xl` on a `<p>`), truncation widths on text. Touch targets growing with type is an a11y win.
- **Don't** modify `@theshyre/design-tokens` to remove the `<html>` override — type and portal content (tooltips/modals/dropdowns) depend on it.
- Form-field grids (`grid-cols-2 gap-4` for First/Last in a fixed-width column) stay rem — swing is ~4px and the grid lives inside an already-fixed parent.
- Common conversions (16px root): `w-48 → w-[192px]`, `w-64 → w-[256px]`, `max-w-sm → max-w-[384px]`, `max-w-md → max-w-[448px]`, `max-w-2xl → max-w-[672px]`, `max-w-7xl → max-w-[1280px]`, `max-h-48 → max-h-[192px]`, `max-h-60 → max-h-[240px]`, `gap-8/px-8 → gap-[32px]/px-[32px]`.

## Redundant visual encoding (MANDATORY)

Every meaningful UI element uses 2+ of: icon, text, color.
- Status: color + text (never color alone)
- Buttons: icon + text
- Errors/warnings/success: color + icon + text

## Keyboard shortcuts (MANDATORY)

- Every primary action has a shortcut with visible `<kbd>` badge
- `/` focuses search, `N` = new item, `Cmd+S` = save, `Escape` = cancel
- `Space` = start/stop timer (when no input focused)

## i18n (MANDATORY)

- `next-intl` — every user-facing string uses `t("key")`
- Locales: `en`, `es` in `src/lib/i18n/locales/{locale}/{namespace}.json`
- Server: `getTranslations()`, Client: `useTranslations()`
- No hardcoded text in components

## Overlays

- Default: inline expansion (1-3 fields)
- Dropdown panel: forms needing more space
- Modal: destructive confirmations or complex multi-step only
- All overlays dismissible via Escape. No nested modals.

## Autosave feedback (MANDATORY)

- Silent saves are a bug. Any form that writes on blur/debounce/toggle without an explicit Save button must render `<SaveStatus />`.
- Source of truth: `useAutosaveStatus()` from `@/hooks/useAutosaveStatus`. Wrap each server-action call with `save.wrap(action(fd))`.
- Indicator: `<SaveStatus status={...} lastSavedAt={...} />` from `@/components/SaveStatus`. Three-channel (icon + color + text): "Saving…" / "Saved just now / Nm ago" / "Save failed".
- Pair with Undo toast + `/trash` when the autosave can destroy data (see Destructive flows).

## Navigation feedback (MANDATORY)

- Every in-app navigation must give visible feedback within 100ms.
- `<TopProgressBar />` is mounted in the root layout; it fires on any in-app `<a>` click and snaps to complete on pathname change. Don't roll a per-page bar.
- `<LinkPendingSpinner />` (uses `useLinkStatus` from `next/link`) goes inside every navigation `<Link>`'s children — sidebar items, dashboard cards, doc index links. Per-link spinner so users see *which* link they hit.
- Add a `loading.tsx` next to any `page.tsx` whose server render does non-trivial work. Keep skeletons simple — TopProgressBar already signals "loading"; loading.tsx just keeps the layout from emptying.
- For non-link interactions (server actions, mutations), use `<SubmitButton>` per the form rules — not the progress bar.

## Tooltips (MANDATORY)

- Use `<Tooltip>` from `@theshyre/ui` (via `@/components/Tooltip`). Native `title=` is banned in new TSX; ESLint enforces this.
- **Required**: icon-only controls (incl. disabled, via `showOnDisabled`); ellipsis-truncated identity/state cells; abbreviations / initialisms / terse codes; color-only chips; "coming soon" placeholders.
- **Forbidden**: form validation errors (use `<FieldError>`); critical info that must always be visible; long-form content (use a popover); duplicating a visible label; nesting.
- **Content**: ≤80 chars, single line preferred, i18n'd, no HTML, never duplicates the trigger's visible label. Keyboard shortcuts render inside via the `shortcut` prop as `<kbd>`.
- **Behavior**: 500 ms hover-open / 0 ms focus-open / 100 ms close; hoverable bubble (WCAG 2.1 SC 1.4.13); Escape dismisses; one tooltip open at a time; top-default auto-flipping; no arrow; `@media (hover: none)` suppresses; `prefers-reduced-motion` disables the fade.
- **A11y**: `aria-describedby` default; `labelMode="label"` wires `aria-label` for icon-only no-other-name triggers (never double-announce). Bubble uses `bg-content` / `text-content-inverse` / `border-edge` — AA across all three themes.

## Documentation (MANDATORY)

- Docs live in `docs/` and are served in-app at `/docs` via react-markdown + remark-gfm.
- Structure: `docs/guides/features/` for cross-role feature docs (apply to everyone), `docs/guides/{agency,bookkeeper,admin}/` for role-specific additions only. `docs/reference/` for technical, `docs/security/` for audit log, `docs/personas/` for AI personas.
- The `/docs` landing is role-aware: surfaces relevant links based on logged-in user's role mix. Audience browse cards are secondary, not the hero.
- Every user-facing feature has a guide in `docs/guides/features/`, shipped in the same commit as the feature. Add a role-specific entry only if something is genuinely role-only.
- Required updates per change:
  - New feature → `docs/guides/features/<feature>.md` (+ role-specific only if needed)
  - Schema change → `docs/reference/database-schema.md`
  - New module / shell concept → `docs/reference/modules.md`
  - New env var → `.env.example` AND `docs/guides/admin/env-configuration.md`
  - Security change → `docs/security/SECURITY_AUDIT_LOG.md` (append-only)
  - Deferred / unshipped → noted in the relevant guide + `docs/personas/README.md`
- Guide format: title → where it lives → how-to steps → constraints / permissions → keyboard shortcuts → related links. ≤ ~200 lines; split if it grows.
- Don't duplicate content across guides. Write once; link from the others.
- Don't leave stale guides when features are removed. Delete or mark deprecated with a date.
- "Shipped but undocumented" is not shipped.

## Proactive development

- Fix issues immediately — no TODOs, no deferring
- Every feature: complete, tested, documented, localized
- Be proactive about improvements

## Personas (MANDATORY)

- Source of truth: `docs/personas/*.md` (8 personas). Tool wrappers at `.claude/agents/` and `.cursor/rules/persona-*.mdc` must reference the source, not duplicate it.
- Auto-engage alongside regular work when these patterns are touched:
  - `src/**/*.ts(x)` or `supabase/migrations/**` → QA Tester
  - `supabase/migrations/**`, `src/lib/supabase/**`, `src/lib/safe-action.ts`, `src/lib/system-admin.ts`, `src/lib/team-context.ts`, `**/actions.ts`, `src/app/auth/**` → Security Reviewer
  - `src/app/**/*.tsx`, `src/components/**/*.tsx` → UX Designer **and** Accessibility Auditor (separate passes)
  - `src/lib/modules/**`, `supabase/migrations/**`, new `(dashboard)/*/page.tsx` → Platform Architect
- Stakeholder voices (Solo Consultant, Agency Owner, Bookkeeper) are **manual invoke only** — engaging them on every change is noise.
- **Persona sync rule:** every persona has three files — `docs/personas/<name>.md`, `.claude/agents/<name>.md`, `.cursor/rules/persona-<name>.mdc`. Editing any one requires editing the other two in the same commit.
- Personas review, they don't implement. Each file ends with a concrete checklist, ≤100 lines.
- Personas are lenses, not gatekeepers — conflicting reviews are fine; the human decides.
- Prune checks that become lint rules / tests. Update personas when prod surprises slip past them.
